{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503828"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2084"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.77,0.05,0.01,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106265"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2084"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88733"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"226"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106265"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman is admitted to the Medical Oncology ward with a history of metastatic thyroid cancer. The nurse becomes concerned because she is difficult to rouse and struggles to remain awake during conversation. She describes ongoing constant pain between her scapulae, which she has had for many weeks and limits her mobility. She also reports significant anxiety regarding her prognosis, and has trouble sleeping at night. She has been prescribed temazepam to help sleep recently. She has no current shortness of breath, cough, or chest pain. She has used multiple analgesic agents in the last few hours but cannot provide a clear history of which medications she has used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she has a respiratory rate of 10/min, oxygen saturation of 89% on room air, pulse rate is 60/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her chest is clear to auscultation. An arterial blood gas (ABG) is performed and reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.25 (7.35 - 7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E: 60 mmHg (80 - 100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E: 60 mmHg (35 - 45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO\u003Csub\u003E3\u003C/sub\u003E: 26 mmol/L (22 - 26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary embolism","Opioid-induced respiratory depression","Metastatic lung disease","Pneumonia","Benzodiazepine overdose"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and arterial blood gas results in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eopioid-induced respiratory depression\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s low respiratory rate, low oxygen saturation, and difficulty staying awake, combined with recent use of multiple analgesics, strongly suggest opioid toxicity. The ABG shows a respiratory acidosis (low pH, high PaCO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E) with hypoxemia (low PaO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E), characteristic of type II respiratory failure caused by opioid-induced ventilatory impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with tachypnea and tachycardia, which are absent in this case. PE usually causes type I respiratory failure (hypoxemia with normal or low PaCO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E), not the type II failure seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E from thyroid cancer is unlikely to cause such an acute presentation. Thyroid cancer rarely metastasizes to the lungs, and if it did, it would typically cause a more gradual onset of symptoms and would not explain the acute respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, cough, and crackles on auscultation, none of which are present in this case. The clear chest on auscultation makes pneumonia less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzodiazepine overdose\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause respiratory depression, especially in combination with opioids. However, benzodiazepines alone typically do not cause significant respiratory depression to the extent seen in this case. The patient\u0027s recent use of multiple analgesics (likely opioids) makes opioid-induced respiratory depression more likely than benzodiazepine overdose alone. That said, the combination of benzodiazepines and opioids can have a synergistic effect, increasing the risk of respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of recent analgesic use, decreased level of consciousness, respiratory depression, and type II respiratory failure on ABG makes opioid-induced respiratory depression the most likely diagnosis in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid over-usage can easily lead to respiratory failure characterized by hypercapnia and hypoxemia.","Type II respiratory failure is characterized by hypercapnia (PaCO2 \u003E 50 mmHg) and often accompanied by hypoxemia."],"references":["NPS MedicineWise. Chapter: Abnormal Laboratory Results, Section: The interpretation of arterial blood gases. Aust Prescr 2010;33:124-9. DOI: 10.18773/austprescr.2010.059","Boom M, Niesters M, Sarton E, Aarts L, Smith TW, Dahan A. Non-analgesic effects of opioids: opioid-induced respiratory depression. Curr Pharm Des. 2012;18(37):5994-6004. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22747535/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88733"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88733"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T15:26:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T15:26:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2084"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106265"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"